WEB SCRAPING AND EXPLORATORY DATA ANALYSIS OF FACTORS AFFECTING USED PRODUCT PRICES IN THE RESALE MARKET

Web Scraping Overview

Data Collection for Resale Market Analysis

  1. Introduction to Web Scraping

Web scraping is the process of automatically extracting data from websites using programming tools instead of manual collection. In data science projects, web scraping is commonly used when structured datasets are not readily available and real-world data must be collected directly from online platforms.

In this project, web scraping was used to collect used product resale listings from an e-commerce platform in order to analyze pricing patterns, market inefficiencies, and buyerseller behavior.

  1. Need for Web Scraping in This Project

The resale market lacks publicly available, clean datasets that include:

  • Product prices

  • Condition

  • Brand information

  • Shipping cost

  • Warranty status

  • Sales performance

To overcome this limitation, web scraping was adopted to:

  • Collect real-time resale listings

  • Capture pricing variability

  • Reflect actual market behavior

  • Build a dataset suitable for Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

  1. Data Source

The data was scraped from an online resale marketplace (eBay), which provides:

A wide range of used products

Transparent pricing and shipping details

Product condition and seller information

Sales and popularity indicators

This platform was chosen due to its large resale ecosystem and data richness.

  1. Tools & Libraries Used

The following Python libraries were used for web scraping:

  • Requests To send HTTP requests and fetch web pages

  • BeautifulSoup (bs4) To parse HTML content and extract required elements

  • Pandas To store and structure scraped data

  • Time To control request frequency and avoid overloading the website

  1. Web Scraping Methodology

The scraping process followed a structured and ethical approach:

Step 1: Sending HTTP Requests

An HTTP request was sent to the target webpage containing resale listings to retrieve the HTML content.

Step 2: Parsing HTML Content

The retrieved HTML was parsed using BeautifulSoup to locate specific HTML tags corresponding to:

  • Product name

  • Brand

  • Price range

  • Shipping cost

  • Condition

  • Warranty information

  • Sales count (if available)

Step 3: Extracting Relevant Fields

Each listing was iterated through, and relevant attributes were extracted using:

  • HTML class names

  • Tag hierarchies

  • CSS selectors

Step 4: Data Storage

The extracted data was stored in:

  • Python lists

  • Converted into a Pandas DataFrame

  • Exported as a CSV file for further analysis

Step 5: Data Cleaning

  • Post-scraping, the data was cleaned by:

  • Removing missing values

  • Converting price strings to numeric format

  • Standardizing condition and brand names

  1. Sample Web Scraping Code (Conceptual) import requests from bs4 import BeautifulSoup import pandas as pd

url = "https://www.ebay.com/sch/i.html?_nkw=used+smartphone" response = requests.get(url)

soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, "html.parser")

products = soup.find_all("div", class_="s-item")

data = []

for item in products: name = item.find("span", class_="s-item__title") price = item.find("span", class_="s-item__price") shipping = item.find("span", class_="s-item__shipping")

if name and price:
    data.append({
        "Product_Name": name.text,
        "Price": price.text,
        "Shipping": shipping.text if shipping else "Not Available"
    })

df = pd.DataFrame(data)

(Note: This code demonstrates the scraping logic used in the project notebook.)

  1. Ethical Considerations

Only publicly available data was collected

No personal user data was scraped

Request frequency was controlled to prevent server overload

The data was used strictly for academic and analytical purposes

  1. Outcome of Web Scraping

The web scraping process resulted in:

  • A structured dataset of resale listings

  • Real-world pricing information

  • Rich attributes for EDA and hypothesis testing

  • This dataset served as the foundation for analyzing resale price behavior and market inefficiencies.

  1. Conclusion

Web scraping enabled the collection of authentic resale market data that would otherwise be unavailable. By leveraging Python-based scraping techniques, this project successfully transformed unstructured web data into a structured dataset suitable for exploratory analysis, visualization, and statistical testing.

import pandas as pd
import re

# Step 1: Load Data
df = pd.read_csv(r"C:\Users\hi\Downloads\raw_data (1).csv")

# Step 2: Extract Brand
brand_pattern = r'(Apple|Samsung|Google|Motorola|Nokia|Xiaomi|Redmi|Poco|UMIDIGI)'
df['Brand'] = df['Name'].str.extract(brand_pattern, expand=False)

# Step 3: Extract Storage (GB / TB)
df['Storage'] = df['Name'].str.extract(r'(\d+\s?(?:GB|TB))', expand=False)

# Step 4: Extract Condition
condition_pattern = r'(New|Excellent|Very Good|Good|Refurbished|Sealed)'
df['Condition'] = df['Name'].str.extract(condition_pattern, expand=False)

# Step 5: Extract Network / Lock Status
network_pattern = r'(Unlocked|T-Mobile|AT&T|Verizon|GSM\+CDMA)'
df['Network'] = df['Name'].str.extract(network_pattern, expand=False)

# Step 6: Extract Model (remove brand, storage, condition, network)
def extract_model(name, brand):
    if pd.isna(name) or pd.isna(brand):
        return None
    
    text = name
    
    # Remove brand
    text = re.sub(brand, '', text, flags=re.IGNORECASE)
    
    # Remove storage
    text = re.sub(r'\d+\s?(?:GB|TB)', '', text, flags=re.IGNORECASE)
    
    # Remove condition
    text = re.sub(condition_pattern, '', text, flags=re.IGNORECASE)
    
    # Remove network info
    text = re.sub(network_pattern, '', text, flags=re.IGNORECASE)
    
    # Remove extra symbols and spaces
    text = re.sub(r'[-|,()]', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'\s+', ' ', text)
    
    return text.strip()

df['Model'] = df.apply(lambda x: extract_model(x['Name'], x['Brand']), axis=1)

# Step 7: Remaining Info (optional column)
df['Other_Info'] = df['Name'].str.replace(brand_pattern, '', regex=True)
df['Other_Info'] = df['Other_Info'].str.replace(r'\d+\s?(?:GB|TB)', '', regex=True)
df['Other_Info'] = df['Other_Info'].str.replace(condition_pattern, '', regex=True)
df['Other_Info'] = df['Other_Info'].str.replace(network_pattern, '', regex=True)
df['Other_Info'] = df['Other_Info'].str.replace(r'\s+', ' ', regex=True).str.strip()

# Final Output
final_df = df[['Name', 'Brand', 'Model', 'Storage', 'Condition', 'Network']]
print(final_df.head())

def clean_price(price):
    if pd.isna(price):
        return np.nan
    
    price = str(price).lower()
    
    # Remove currency symbols and commas
    price = price.replace("", "").replace("$", "").replace(",", "").strip()
    
    # Case 1: Price range like "359.99 to 424.99"
    if "to" in price:
        parts = price.split("to")
        nums = []
        for p in parts:
            p = p.strip()
            try:
                nums.append(float(p))
            except:
                pass
        
        if len(nums) == 2:
            return round(sum(nums) / 2, 2)   # average of range
    
    # Case 2: Single price like "172.99"
    try:
        return round(float(price), 2)
    except:
        return np.nan

import pandas as pd
import re

# ================= LOAD DATA =================
df = pd.read_csv(r"C:\Users\hi\Downloads\raw_data (1).csv")

# ================= PRODUCT TYPE SPLIT =================
split_df = (
    df['Product_Type']
    .astype(str)
    .replace('nan', '')
    .str.split('  ', n=1, expand=True)
    .reindex(columns=[0, 1])
)

df['Condition'] = split_df[0].replace('', 'N/A')
df['Brand'] = split_df[1].replace('', 'N/A')

# ================= FUNCTIONS =================
def extract_rom(name):
    if pd.isna(name):
        return "N/A"
    name = str(name)
    m = re.search(r'(\d+)\s*(GB|TB)\s*(ROM|Storage|Internal|Memory)', name, re.I)
    if m:
        v, u = int(m.group(1)), m.group(2).upper()
        if u == 'TB' or v >= 32:
            return f"{v}{u}"
    for v, u in re.findall(r'(\d+)\s*(GB|TB)', name, re.I):
        v = int(v)
        if u.upper() == 'TB' or v >= 32:
            return f"{v}{u.upper()}"
    return "N/A"

def clean_name_extreme(name):
    if pd.isna(name):
        return "N/A"
    name = str(name)
    name = re.sub(r'\d+(?:\s*/\s*\d+)*\s*(GB|TB|MB|RAM|ROM)', '', name, flags=re.I)
    name = re.sub(r'[\"\(\)\[\]\-\.\/\|,\*\+]', ' ', name)
    noise = [
        'Unlocked','Factory','Fully','Excellent','Very Good','Good Condition',
        'Brand New','Pre Owned','Refurbished','All Colors','Free Shipping',
        'Free Returns','Warranty','Global Version','GSM','LTE','5G','4G',
        'Dual SIM','Storage','Internal','Memory','Condition'
    ]
    for w in noise:
        name = re.sub(r'\b' + w + r'\b', '', name, flags=re.I)
    return re.sub(r'\s+', ' ', name).strip()

def clean_price(p):
    if pd.isna(p):
        return 0.0, 0.0
    s = str(p).replace('$', '').replace(',', '')
    if ' to ' in s:
        a, b = s.split(' to ')
        return float(a), float(b)
    v = float(s) if s else 0.0
    return v, v

# ================= APPLY TRANSFORMATIONS =================
df['ROM'] = df['Name'].apply(extract_rom)

df['Warranty'] = df['Type'].apply(
    lambda x: re.search(
        r'(\d+\s*(?:Yr|Year|Month|Day)s?\s*Warranty)',
        str(x),
        re.I
    ).group(1)
    if re.search(r'(\d+\s*(?:Yr|Year|Month|Day)s?\s*Warranty)', str(x), re.I)
    else "0"
)

df['Name'] = df['Name'].apply(clean_name_extreme)

prices = df['Price'].apply(clean_price)
df['Min_Price'] = [p[0] for p in prices]
df['Max_Price'] = [p[1] for p in prices]

df['Shipment_Cost'] = df['Shipment'].apply(
    lambda x: float(re.search(r'(\d+\.?\d*)', str(x)).group(1))
    if pd.notna(x) and 'Free' not in str(x)
    else 0.0
)

df['Sold_Count'] = df['NO_of_sold'].apply(
    lambda x: int(re.search(r'([\d,]+)', str(x)).group(1).replace(',', ''))
    if pd.notna(x) and 'sold' in str(x).lower()
    else 0
)

# ================= FINAL DATAFRAME =================
df_final = df[
    ['Name','Brand','Condition','ROM','Warranty',
     'Min_Price','Max_Price','Shipment_Cost','Sold_Count']
].fillna('N/A')

# ================= RENAME COLUMNS WITH $ =================
df_final = df_final.rename(columns={
    'Min_Price': 'Min_Price ($)',
    'Max_Price': 'Max_Price ($)',
    'Shipment_Cost': 'Shipment_Cost ($)'
})

# ================= SAVE FILE =================
df_final.to_csv('cleaneda_dataa.csv', index=False)

print("Data cleaned and saved successfully")

Basic Understanding

Exploratory Data Analysis of Factors Affecting Used Product Prices in the Resale Market

  1. Introduction

The resale market for used electronic products has grown rapidly due to affordability concerns and sustainability awareness. However, this market suffers from significant information asymmetry, where sellers and buyers lack reliable, data-driven pricing insights.

As a result:

Sellers risk underpricing, leading to profit loss, or overpricing, leading to unsold inventory.

Buyers struggle to distinguish between fairly priced products and overpriced listings.

Important factors such as product condition, brand value, storage capacity, shipping costs, and warranty are often ignored, causing market inefficiencies.

This project aims to address these issues through Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) to identify the key factors influencing resale prices and sales performance.

  1. Problem Statement

There is a lack of data-driven insights in the resale market, resulting in inconsistent pricing strategies and inefficient buyerseller decision-making.

  1. Objectives of the Study

The key objectives of this project are:

  • To analyze the distribution of resale prices in the used product market.

  • To examine the impact of brand, condition, storage (ROM), warranty, and shipping cost on resale price.

  • To understand how pricing affects sales volume.

  • To identify overpriced and underpriced listings.

  • To provide actionable insights for sellers and buyers to improve market efficiency.

  1. Dataset Description

The dataset contains cleaned resale listings with the following attributes:

  • Brand Manufacturer of the product

  • Condition Product condition (New, Refurbished, Pre-Owned, etc.)

  • ROM Storage capacity

  • Min Price / Max Price Price range of listings

  • Shipment Cost Shipping charges

  • Warranty Warranty availability (Yes/No)

  • Sold Count Number of units sold

A derived variable, Average Price, was calculated as the mean of minimum and maximum prices to represent a fair resale price.

  1. Methodology

The project followed these steps:

  • Data Cleaning & Preparation

  • Removed inconsistencies

  • Standardized column formats

  • Created derived features (Average Price)

  • Exploratory Data Analysis

  • Univariate, bivariate, and multivariate analysis

  • Statistical summaries and visualizations

  • Visualization

  • Publication-quality plots using Seaborn and Matplotlib

  • Color-coded charts for interpretability

  • Hypothesis Testing

  • ANOVA, t-tests, and correlation analysis

  • Statistical validation of observed patterns

  1. Exploratory Data Analysis & Key Findings 6.1 Price Distribution

The resale prices exhibit a wide and right-skewed distribution, indicating:

  • Presence of both budget and premium listings

  • Lack of standardized pricing benchmarks

  • Insight: The wide spread confirms market inconsistency and the need for structured pricing strategies.

6.2 Brand Impact on Resale Price

Analysis shows that brand has a strong influence on resale value:

  • Premium brands command significantly higher average prices.

Some brands also exhibit higher sales volume, indicating strong demand.

Insight: Brand reputation creates a resale price premium.

6.3 Product Condition vs Price

Product condition has a significant impact on pricing:

New and refurbished products fetch higher prices.

Poor-condition products show greater price variability.

Insight: Condition-based pricing is essential to avoid buyer distrust and seller loss.

6.4 Storage Capacity (ROM)

Resale price increases with storage capacity, but:

The price increment diminishes at higher ROM levels.

Insight: Mid-tier storage options offer the best value-for-money balance.

6.5 Shipping Cost and Sales Volume

A negative relationship exists between shipping cost and units sold:

Listings with free or low shipping sell more.

High shipping costs discourage buyers.

Insight: Shipping cost is a hidden factor contributing to market inefficiency.

6.6 Price vs Sales Volume

Higher prices generally lead to lower sales volume.

Overpriced listings show low demand.

Competitively priced listings achieve higher turnover.

Insight: Sellers must balance profit margin and sales velocity.

  1. Hypothesis Testing Summary Hypothesis Test Used Result Condition affects price ANOVA Rejected H Brand affects price ANOVA Rejected H Shipping cost affects sales Pearson correlation Rejected H Warranty increases price t-test Rejected H Price affects sales Correlation Rejected H

Conclusion: All tested factors have a statistically significant impact.

  1. Key Business Insights
  • For Sellers:

Use brand- and condition-based pricing

Offer free or low shipping when possible

Avoid overpricing high-ROM products

  • For Buyers:

Compare prices adjusted for condition and shipping

Best deals often exist in mid-range configurations

  • For the Market:

Data-driven pricing reduces information asymmetry

Improves transparency and trust

  1. Conclusion

This exploratory analysis demonstrates that resale prices are influenced by multiple interconnected factors rather than a single attribute. The lack of data-driven pricing leads to inefficiencies, buyer confusion, and lost revenue opportunities.
